{"title_page": "Freeboard (nautical)", "text_new": "{{short description|Distance from the waterline to the upper deck level of a ship}}\n[[File:Ship length measurements.svg|thumb|right|300px|A graphical representation of the dimensions used to describe a ship. ''f'' is the freeboard.]]\n{{redirect|Freeboard|the specialist skateboard|Freeboard (skateboard)}}\n\nIn [[sailing]] and [[boating]], a vessel's '''freeboard'''\nis the distance from the [[waterline]] to the upper [[deck (ship)|deck]] level, measured at the lowest point of [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]] where water can enter the [[boat]] or [[ship]].<ref>{{cite web\n   | last = \n   | first = \n   | authorlink = \n   | title = IMO\n   | work = \n   | publisher = \n   | date = 2008\n   | url = http://www.imo.org/conventions/mainframe.asp?topic_id=1034\n   | format = \n   | doi = \n   | accessdate = 2008-04-16\n   | archive-url = http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091014024227/http://www.imo.org/Conventions/mainframe.asp?topic_id=1034\n   | archive-date = 2009-10-14\n   | url-status = dead\n   }}</ref> In commercial vessels, the latter criterion measured relative to the [[waterline|ship's load line]], regardless of deck arrangements, is the mandated and regulated meaning.<ref name=\"3defs\">{{Cite web|title=Dictionary.com definitions of \"Freeboard\"|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/freeboard|accessdate=2008-06-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080416181555/http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/freeboard|archive-date=2008-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn yachts, a low freeboard is often found on [[Yacht racing|racing boats]], for increased speed (by reducing weight and therefore drag).  A higher freeboard will give more room in the [[cabin (ship)|cabin]], but will increase weight and drag, compromising speed. A higher freeboard, such as used on [[ocean liners]], also helps weather waves and so reduce the likelihood of being washed over by full water waves on the [[Weather deck#Weather deck|weather deck]].  A low-freeboard boat is susceptible to taking in water in rough seas. Freighter ships and [[warship]]s use high freeboard designs to increase internal volume, which also allows them to satisfy [[International Maritime Organization]] (IMO) damage stability regulations, due to increased [[Waterline#Purpose|reserve buoyancy]].\n\n==See also==\n*For the term as used in measuring sea ice, see [[Sea ice thickness]].\n*[[Narco-submarine]], a type of vessel that often is a surface ship with a very low freeboard.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Hayler |first=William B. |author2=Keever, John M. |title=American Merchant Seaman's Manual |year=2003 |publisher= Cornell Maritime Pr |isbn= 0-87033-549-9 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Turpin | first = Edward A. | authorlink =  |author2=McEwen, William A. | title = Merchant Marine life.  Officers' Handbook | url =  | edition = 4th | series =  | year = 1980 | publisher =Cornell Maritime Press  | location = Centreville, MD | isbn = 0-87033-056-X | pages =  | chapter =  | chapterurl = }}\n\n{{Ship measurements}}\n\n[[Category:Nautical terminology]]\n[[Category:Ship measurements]]\n\n[[de:Schiffsma\u00dfe#Freibord]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Distance from the waterline to the upper deck level of a ship}}\n[[File:Ship length measurements.svg|thumb|right|300px|A graphical representation of the dimensions used to describe a ship. ''f'' is the freeboard.]]\n{{redirect|Freeboard|the specialist skateboard|Freeboard (skateboard)}}\n\nIn [[sailing]] and [[boating]], a vessel's '''freeboard'''\nis the distance from the [[waterline]] to the upper [[deck (ship)|deck]] level, measured at the lowest point of [[Sheer (ship)|sheer]] where water can enter the [[boat]] or [[ship]].<ref>{{cite web\n   | last = \n   | first = \n   | authorlink = \n   | title = IMO\n   | work = \n   | publisher = \n   | date = 2008\n   | url = http://www.imo.org/conventions/mainframe.asp?topic_id=1034\n   | format = \n   | doi = 